  "assets": [
    {
      "assetId": "phys.meas.units/core_explanation/1",
      "kind": "core_explanation",
      "conceptId": "phys.meas.units",
      "title": "SI Base Units — core idea",
      "content": "The International System of Units (SI) defines seven base units — each representing a fundamental, independently measurable physical quantity. Every other unit in science is derived from these seven. The base units are: metre (m, length), kilogram (kg, mass), second (s, time), ampere (A, electric current), kelvin (K, thermodynamic temperature), mole (mol, amount of substance), candela (cd, luminous intensity).",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.meas.units.md",
        "startLine": 9,
        "endLine": 36
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.meas.units/learning_objective/1",
      "kind": "learning_objective",
      "conceptId": "phys.meas.units",
      "title": "Learning Objective",
      "content": "Given a physical quantity (length, mass, time, electric current, temperature, amount of substance, luminous intensity), the student:\n\n(a) correctly names the SI base unit for that quantity;  \n(b) correctly states the symbol for that unit;  \n(c) correctly classifies a given unit as an SI base unit or not.\n\n**Accuracy threshold:** 70% across all recall items (consistent with bloom=remember + difficulty=foundational).\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.meas.units.md",
        "startLine": 36,
        "endLine": 48
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.meas.units/misconception/MC-1",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.meas.units",
      "title": "— Degree Celsius Is the SI Temperature Unit",
      "content": "### MC-1 — Degree Celsius Is the SI Temperature Unit\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student names °C as the SI base unit for temperature; converts \"0°C = 0 K\"; writes temperature in °C in SI calculations.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2a; TA-A04 classification.\n\n**Root cause:** Celsius is the dominant temperature unit in everyday life in most countries. Kelvin is rarely encountered outside formal physics/chemistry. \"Temperature\" in daily conversation means Celsius.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 → P07 (scale comparison) → P28 (absolute zero argument) → P29 → P30 (physical meaning of zero) → P31 (install K as base) → P32 (K↔°C conversion practice)\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-1"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.meas.units.md",
        "startLine": 5,
        "endLine": 19
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.meas.units/misconception/MC-2",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.meas.units",
      "title": "— Mass and Weight Are the Same Quantity",
      "content": "### MC-2 — Mass and Weight Are the Same Quantity\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student uses kg and N interchangeably; says \"my weight is 70 kg\" without qualification.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** Assessment AB-1; or spontaneous statement during session.\n\n*Note: Full repair of MC-2 (mass vs. weight as force) requires phys.meas.scalars-vectors and phys.mech.force — concepts not yet in student's map at this stage. Address only the following: \"kg measures mass, not weight. Weight is a force and has its own unit (the Newton) which is derived.\" Full conceptual repair is deferred to phys.mech.newton-laws blueprint.*\n\n**Repair chain (partial):** P27 → P07 (two columns: mass vs. weight) → P30 (bridge: kg = mass = how much matter; N = weight = gravitational force on that mass) → P31 (install minimal distinction)\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent. Partial repair only at this blueprint level.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-2"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.meas.units.md",
        "startLine": 19,
        "endLine": 33
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.meas.units/misconception/MC-3",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.meas.units",
      "title": "— Common Units (Litre, Centimetre, Hour) Are SI Base Units",
      "content": "### MC-3 — Common Units (Litre, Centimetre, Hour) Are SI Base Units\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student classifies L, cm, or hr as SI base units; or states SI has more than 7 base units.\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2c; TA-A04 classification.\n\n**Root cause:** These units are used alongside SI units in most school contexts without explicit labelling of their status.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 → P07 (non-SI conversion table) → P17 (contrast: SI base vs. derived multiples vs. non-SI) → P31 → P33 (discrimination training: sort 10 units into SI base / SI derived / non-SI)\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-3",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-3"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.meas.units.md",
        "startLine": 33,
        "endLine": 47
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.meas.units/misconception/MC-4",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.meas.units",
      "title": "— Gram (Not Kilogram) Is the SI Mass Base Unit",
      "content": "### MC-4 — Gram (Not Kilogram) Is the SI Mass Base Unit\n\n**Observable symptom:** Student writes \"g\" as the SI base unit for mass; derives \"kg = 1000 g (derived unit).\"\n\n**Diagnostic trigger:** DB-2b; TA-A04 classification.\n\n**Root cause:** Gram is smaller and more intuitive for everyday objects. The \"kilo\" prefix pattern in metric teaching typically positions gram as fundamental and kilogram as derived.\n\n**Repair chain:** P27 → P07 (SI prefix table showing kg as uniquely having prefix in base name) → P28 (historical anomaly argument) → P30 (exception: kg is the defined base despite the prefix) → P31 → P32 (3 examples always using kg, not g, in SI calculations)\n\n**MAMR status:** Independent.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-4",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-4"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.meas.units.md",
        "startLine": 47,
        "endLine": 61
      }
    },
